Note: ============================================================================
Note: destroy_cross_module_optimizer - Deep-clean teardown
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
destroy_cross_module_optimizer releases every collection owned by the CMO
struct and then deallocates the struct itself. The deep-clean policy was
ratified by the CEO during P1-E v2 review: every collection allocated by
create_cross_module_optimizer is destroyed here in matching order.

The CMO struct (104 bytes) owns:
- inline_candidates  (offset 72): List of CrossModuleInlineCandidate pointers
- value_map          (offset 80): Dictionary
- function_clones    (offset 88): Dictionary
- optimization_stats (offset 96): Dictionary

The wpa pointer at offset 0 is borrowed (owned by optimize_program's stack
frame, destroyed separately by destroy_whole_program_analysis). The mir
pointer at offset 8 is also borrowed (owned by compile_program's arena).

Per-candidate allocations inside inline_candidates are 80-byte
CrossModuleInlineCandidate structs allocated by select_inlining_candidates.
Each is freed before the parent list is destroyed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Idempotent for cmo == 0 (returns 0 without crashing). Defensive null checks
on every contained pointer because create_cross_module_optimizer can succeed
with some collections initialized and others not (allocator pressure case).

Free order is the reverse of allocation order: Dictionary handles first
(no contained pointers we own), then per-candidate structs, then the
candidates List, then the CMO struct itself.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Called exactly once per compile job at end of Phase D of optimize_program.
Cost is O(|inline_candidates|) for the per-candidate free loop, plus
constant-time Dictionary destruction. Negligible compared to optimization
cost.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. Releases owned heap memory; does not touch borrowed
WPA or MIR pointers. Misuse (calling twice on the same cmo) is guarded by
the cmo == 0 early-out.
@End Security_Scope

