Note: ============================================================================
Note: Priority-driven optimization (O3 path)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
sort_priority_dict_descending sorts the bucket-tagged keys of the priority
Dictionary by their associated priority scores in descending order. The
resulting List contains op_id values (bucket-tagged keys); the consumer
decodes bucket+index per the design's encoding.

This is a stable merge sort over O(n) entries where n is the total number
of optimization candidates across all buckets - typically O(|MIR| / 100)
for realistic programs. Mirrors the merge-sort pattern in
rank_optimization_candidates (whole_program_analysis.runa) which sorts
within a single bucket.

Algorithm: extract keys list from the Dict, then run a top-down merge sort
keyed by the priority score (Dict.get(priorities, key)). Stable means
equal scores preserve insertion order, giving deterministic output across
runs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns a freshly allocated List of op_ids sorted by score descending.
The original priorities Dict is not mutated. Uses iterative bottom-up
merge sort to avoid stack recursion limits on large candidate sets.

Stability: when two op_ids have equal scores, the one that came earlier
in the keys list wins. This is the standard "less-than (not less-or-equal)
keeps left" merge predicate.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(n log n) where n = candidate count. For n=500, ~4500 comparisons - well
under one millisecond. Allocates one auxiliary List of size n for the
merge pass.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. Reads the priority Dict (does not mutate). The returned
List is owned by the caller (typically the priority-driven dispatcher,
which iterates it and then lets it go out of scope).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "sort_priority_dict_descending" that takes priorities as Integer returns Integer:
    If priorities is equal to 0:
        Return proc create from List
    End If

    Note: Extract keys list (ownership: keys list is freshly allocated by Dictionary.keys)
    Let keys be proc keys from Dictionary with priorities
    If keys is equal to 0:
        Return proc create from List
    End If

    Let n be proc length from List with keys
    If n is less than 2:
        Return keys
    End If

    Note: Bottom-up merge sort. width doubles each pass; merge adjacent runs.
    Let aux be proc create from List
    Let aux_i be 0
    While aux_i is less than n:
        proc append from List with aux, 0
        Set aux_i to aux_i plus 1
    End While

    Let width be 1
    While width is less than n:
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than n:
            Note: Merge runs [i, i+width) and [i+width, i+2*width)
            Let left_end be i plus width
            If left_end is greater than n:
                Set left_end to n
            End If
            Let right_end be i plus (width plus width)
            If right_end is greater than n:
                Set right_end to n
            End If

            Let left_pos be i
            Let right_pos be left_end
            Let out_pos be i

            While out_pos is less than right_end:
                Let take_left be 0
                If left_pos is less than left_end:
                    If right_pos is greater than or equal to right_end:
                        Set take_left to 1
                    Otherwise:
                        Let lk be proc get from List with keys, left_pos
                        Let rk be proc get from List with keys, right_pos
                        Let ls be proc get from Dictionary with priorities, lk
                        Let rs be proc get from Dictionary with priorities, rk
                        Note: Descending: left wins when ls >= rs (stable)
                        If ls is greater than or equal to rs:
                            Set take_left to 1
                        End If
                    End If
                End If

                If take_left is equal to 1:
                    Let lk2 be proc get from List with keys, left_pos
                    proc set from List with aux, out_pos, lk2
                    Set left_pos to left_pos plus 1
                Otherwise:
                    Let rk2 be proc get from List with keys, right_pos
                    proc set from List with aux, out_pos, rk2
                    Set right_pos to right_pos plus 1
                End If

                Set out_pos to out_pos plus 1
            End While

            Set i to i plus (width plus width)
        End While

        Note: Copy aux back to keys for next pass
        Let c be 0
        While c is less than n:
            Let val be proc get from List with aux, c
            proc set from List with keys, c, val
            Set c to c plus 1
        End While

        Set width to width plus width
    End While

    proc destroy from List with aux

    Return keys
End Process

@Reasoning
apply_inlining_candidate applies a single cross-module inlining transform
identified by index into wpa.inlining_candidates.

This is the priority-bucket dispatch wrapper for bucket 0x0001. It is the
per-candidate counterpart to perform_cross_module_inlining (which applies
all candidates in bulk). The priority-driven path needs per-candidate
granularity so the priority ordering can interleave inlining with other
buckets (devirt, DCE, etc.).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads candidate from wpa.inlining_candidates (offset 112 of WPA) at the
given index. The WPA candidate format is (caller_id, callee_id, benefit)
- a 24-byte tuple (verified at lines 511-513 of select_inlining_candidates).

A transient CrossModuleInlineCandidate is built from the WPA tuple and
passed to inline_function_into_caller (the existing single-candidate
worker, line 580). The transient struct is freed after the call.

If the index is out of range or the candidate pointer is null, returns 0
(no-op). If the inlining transform fails (e.g. caller no longer reachable
post earlier DCE), returns 0. Returns 1 on successful inlining.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) lookup plus the underlying inline_function_into_caller cost (which is
bounded by callee function body size). Allocates one 80-byte transient
struct per call.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. Delegates safety/legality checks to
validate_inline_candidate (called by inline_function_into_caller).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "apply_inlining_candidate" that takes cmo as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let wpa be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cmo, 0
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let wpa_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 112
    If wpa_candidates is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let candidate_count be proc length from List with wpa_candidates
    If index is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
