@Reasoning
apply_devirt_candidate_speculative applies a single speculative
devirtualization transform identified by index into
wpa.devirtualization_candidates.

Bucket 0x0003 dispatches here when the candidate is speculative (a
dominant target exists but not a unique implementation). A guarded
direct-call sequence is inserted: runtime type check + branch to direct
call or fallback to indirect call. For codegen this is tracked as
"potential devirtualization" - the actual CFG splice happens in a later
pass that has block-level CFG mutation primitives.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Same lookup as apply_devirt_candidate_exact, but the candidate is required
to be speculative (confidence == 0). Per the design and the existing
apply_devirtualization comment block, the CFG transformation is staged
(the original opcode is left as CALL_INDIRECT; a flag at instruction
offset 24 is set to mark it for guarded-call expansion later, with the
target_function stored at instruction offset 32 as the speculative
target).

Returns 1 on successful marking, 0 on no-op.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1). Same cost profile as the exact variant.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Speculative devirt is sound only if the runtime guard is preserved through
codegen. If the guard is dropped, the resulting binary may call a wrong
target. The marking here delegates correctness to the downstream guard
expansion pass.
@End Security_Scope

